<body data-topic="database">
<div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center">Types of Databases</h1>
    
    <div class="intro-section">
        <p>Now that you understand what a database is and why we need them, let's explore the different <strong>types of databases</strong> available. Think of this like choosing the right tool for a job - you wouldn't use a hammer to screw in a light bulb!</p>
        
        <p>Each database type has its own strengths and is designed for specific situations. Let's break them down:</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">1. Relational Databases (SQL Databases)</h2>
    
    <div class="database-type">
        <div class="type-header">
            <h4>The "Organized Spreadsheet" Database</h4>
        </div>
        
        <div class="description">
            <p>This is the most common type you'll work with as a beginner. Data is stored in <strong>tables</strong> (like Excel spreadsheets) that can be connected with relationships.</p>
            
            <div class="visual-example">
                <div class="code-container">
                    <div class="code-header">Relational Database Structure</div>
                    <div class="code-content">
<pre>
<span style="color: #198754;">// Students Table</span>
┌─────────┬──────────┬──────┐
│   ID    │   Name   │ Age  │
├─────────┼──────────┼──────┤
│    1    │  Alice   │  20  │
│    2    │   Bob    │  21  │
│    3    │ Charlie  │  19  │
└─────────┴──────────┴──────┘

<span style="color: #198754;">// Courses Table</span>
┌─────┬────────────┬────────────┐
│ ID  │ CourseName │ Instructor │
├─────┼────────────┼────────────┤
│ 101 │   Math     │  Mr.Smith  │
│ 102 │  Science   │ Ms.Johnson │
└─────┴────────────┴────────────┘

<span style="color: #198754;">// Enrollment Table (Connects students to courses)</span>
┌───────────┬───────────┐
│ StudentID │ CourseID  │
├───────────┼───────────┤
│     1     │    101    │ ← Alice takes Math
│     2     │    101    │ ← Bob takes Math
│     3     │    102    │ ← Charlie takes Science
└───────────┴───────────┘
</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="details-grid">
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>Popular Examples:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Microsoft SQL Server</strong> (What we'll use with C#!)</li>
                        <li><strong>MySQL</strong> (Free and popular)</li>
                        <li><strong>PostgreSQL</strong> (Powerful open-source)</li>
                        <li><strong>SQLite</strong> (Lightweight, good for mobile apps)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>Best For:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Structured, predictable data</li>
                        <li>When you need relationships between data</li>
                        <li>Banking systems, school records, online stores</li>
                        <li>Situations where data accuracy is critical</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>C# Integration:</h5>
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header">Easy C# Code Example</div>
                        <div class="code-content">
<pre>
<span style="color: #198754;">// Finding students in Math class</span>
var mathStudents = db.Students
    .Where(s => s.Courses.Any(c => c.Name == "Math"))
    .ToList();

<span style="color: #198754;">// No SQL needed - just C#!</span>
</pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="use-case-box">
                <h5>Perfect Use Case: School Management System</h5>
                <p><strong>Why relational works:</strong> Students, teachers, courses, grades - all have clear relationships and structured data.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">2. NoSQL Databases</h2>
    
    <div class="database-type">
        <div class="type-header">
            <h4>The "Flexible Document" Database</h4>
        </div>
        
        <div class="description">
            <p>NoSQL means "Not Only SQL" - these databases are flexible and don't require fixed tables. Great for when your data structure changes often.</p>
            
            <div class="visual-example">
                <div class="code-container">
                    <div class="code-header">NoSQL Document Structure (JSON-like)</div>
                    <div class="code-content">
<pre>
<span style="color: #198754;">// MongoDB Document Example (stores as flexible JSON)</span>
{
  "_id": "student_123",
  "name": "Alice",
  "age": 20,
  "courses": ["Math", "Science", "Art"],
  "extras": {
    "hobbies": ["Reading", "Swimming"],
    "contact": {
      "email": "alice@school.com",
      "phone": "123-456-7890"
    }
  }
  <span style="color: #198754;">// Note: Each student can have different fields!</span>
}

<span style="color: #198754;">// Another student with different structure</span>
{
  "_id": "student_456",
  "name": "Bob",
  "major": "Computer Science",
  "internship": true,
  "skills": ["C#", "JavaScript", "SQL"]
  <span style="color: #198754;">// No "age" or "courses" field - that's okay!</span>
}
</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="nosql-types">
                <div class="nosql-type">
                    <h5>📄 Document-Based (MongoDB)</h5>
                    <p>Stores data as flexible documents (like JSON). Each document can have different fields.</p>
                    <p><strong>Good for:</strong> Content management, user profiles, catalogs</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="nosql-type">
                    <h5>🗝️ Key-Value (Redis)</h5>
                    <p>Simple storage: key → value. Super fast for caching.</p>
                    <p><strong>Good for:</strong> Session storage, caching, real-time data</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="nosql-type">
                    <h5>📊 Column-Based (Cassandra)</h5>
                    <p>Stores data in columns instead of rows. Great for big data.</p>
                    <p><strong>Good for:</strong> Analytics, logging, time-series data</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="nosql-type">
                    <h5>🕸️ Graph-Based (Neo4j)</h5>
                    <p>Focuses on relationships between data points.</p>
                    <p><strong>Good for:</strong> Social networks, recommendations, fraud detection</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="use-case-box">
                <h5>Perfect Use Case: Social Media App</h5>
                <p><strong>Why NoSQL works:</strong> User profiles have different data, posts have varying content types, relationships change constantly.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">3. In-Memory Databases</h2>
    
    <div class="database-type">
        <div class="type-header">
            <h4>The "Lightning Fast" Database</h4>
        </div>
        
        <div class="description">
            <p>Stores data in computer memory (RAM) instead of on disk. This makes them incredibly fast but more expensive and volatile (data lost when power goes off).</p>
            
            <div class="speed-comparison">
                <div class="speed-item">
                    <h5>Traditional Disk Database</h5>
                    <p>Reads/writes to hard drive</p>
                    <p><strong>Speed:</strong> 5-50 milliseconds</p>
                    <p><strong>Like:</strong> Reading a book from library shelves</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="speed-item fast">
                    <h5>In-Memory Database</h5>
                    <p>Reads/writes to RAM</p>
                    <p><strong>Speed:</strong> 0.1-1 milliseconds</p>
                    <p><strong>Like:</strong> Having the book open on your desk</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="details-grid">
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>Examples:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Redis</strong> (most popular)</li>
                        <li><strong>Memcached</strong></li>
                        <li><strong>Microsoft SQL Server In-Memory</strong></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>Best For:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Caching (storing frequently used data)</li>
                        <li>Real-time analytics</li>
                        <li>Session storage (website login sessions)</li>
                        <li>Leaderboards in games</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>Limitations:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>More expensive (RAM costs more than disk)</li>
                        <li>Data lost when server restarts (unless configured)</li>
                        <li>Limited by available memory</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="use-case-box">
                <h5>Perfect Use Case: Online Game Leaderboard</h5>
                <p><strong>Why in-memory works:</strong> Need to update and show scores in real-time, thousands of times per second.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">4. Cloud Databases</h2>
    
    <div class="database-type">
        <div class="type-header">
            <h4>The "No-Hassle" Database</h4>
        </div>
        
        <div class="description">
            <p>Databases hosted and managed by cloud providers. You don't worry about servers, backups, or maintenance - you just use it!</p>
            
            <div class="cloud-providers">
                <div class="cloud-provider">
                    <h5>Microsoft Azure</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Azure SQL Database</strong> (Relational)</li>
                        <li><strong>Cosmos DB</strong> (NoSQL - very flexible)</li>
                        <li><strong>Azure Cache for Redis</strong> (In-memory)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> C#/.NET developers (seamless integration)</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="cloud-provider">
                    <h5>Amazon AWS</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Amazon RDS</strong> (Relational)</li>
                        <li><strong>DynamoDB</strong> (NoSQL)</li>
                        <li><strong>ElastiCache</strong> (In-memory)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Large-scale applications</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="cloud-provider">
                    <h5>Google Cloud</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Cloud SQL</strong> (Relational)</li>
                        <li><strong>Firestore</strong> (NoSQL)</li>
                        <li><strong>Memorystore</strong> (In-memory)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> AI/ML applications</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="cloud-benefits">
                <div class="benefit">
                    <h5>Automatic Backups</h5>
                    <p>Cloud providers handle backups automatically - you never lose data.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="benefit">
                    <h5>Easy Scaling</h5>
                    <p>Need more power? Click a button. Pay only for what you use.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="benefit">
                    <h5>Global Access</h5>
                    <p>Access your database from anywhere with internet.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="benefit">
                    <h5>Security Built-in</h5>
                    <p>Professional security, encryption, and compliance handled for you.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="use-case-box">
                <h5>Perfect Use Case: Startup Company</h5>
                <p><strong>Why cloud works:</strong> No IT staff, need to scale quickly, want to focus on coding not server management.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">5. Simple File-Based Databases</h2>
    
    <div class="database-type">
        <div class="type-header">
            <h4>The "Beginner Friendly" Database</h4>
        </div>
        
        <div class="description">
            <p>Sometimes called "flat-file" databases. These are simple files like CSV, JSON, or XML that store data. No complex setup needed.</p>
            
            <div class="file-examples">
                <div class="code-container">
                    <div class="code-header">CSV File (Comma-Separated Values)</div>
                    <div class="code-content">
<pre>
Name,Age,Grade,Email
Alice,20,A,alice@school.com
Bob,21,B,bob@school.com
Charlie,19,A,charlie@school.com
</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="code-container">
                    <div class="code-header">JSON File (JavaScript Object Notation)</div>
                    <div class="code-content">
<pre>
{
  "students": [
    {
      "name": "Alice",
      "age": 20,
      "grade": "A",
      "email": "alice@school.com"
    },
    {
      "name": "Bob", 
      "age": 21,
      "grade": "B",
      "email": "bob@school.com"
    }
  ]
}
</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="details-grid">
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>When to Use:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Very small applications</li>
                        <li>Learning/experimentation</li>
                        <li>Configuration files</li>
                        <li>Simple data exports</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>Limitations:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>No relationships between data</li>
                        <li>Slow with lots of data</li>
                        <li>No built-in security</li>
                        <li>Hard to search efficiently</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <h5>C# Example:</h5>
                    <div class="code-container">
                        <div class="code-header">Reading from JSON file in C#</div>
                        <div class="code-content">
<pre>
<span style="color: #198754;">// Simple but limited</span>
string jsonText = File.ReadAllText("students.json");
var students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize&lt;List&lt;Student&gt;&gt;(jsonText);

<span style="color: #dc3545;">// Problems: No validation, slow with many records</span>
</pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="use-case-box">
                <h5>Perfect Use Case: Personal Budget Tracker</h5>
                <p><strong>Why file-based works:</strong> Only you use it, small amount of data, simple structure.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="choice-guide">
        <h3 class="text-center">Which Database Should You Choose?</h3>
        
        <div class="guide-table">
            <div class="guide-row header">
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>Choose This Type...</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>When You Need...</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>Good For Beginners?</strong></div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="guide-row">
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>Relational (SQL)</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell">Structured data with clear relationships</div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><span style="color: #198754;">YES - Start here!</span></div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="guide-row">
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>NoSQL</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell">Flexible, changing data structure</div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><span style="color: #ffc107;">Maybe - Learn basics first</span></div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="guide-row">
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>In-Memory</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell">Extreme speed for specific tasks</div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><span style="color: #dc3545;">No - Advanced topic</span></div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="guide-row">
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>Cloud</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell">No server management, easy scaling</div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><span style="color: #198754;">YES - Great for learning</span></div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="guide-row">
                <div class="guide-cell"><strong>File-Based</strong></div>
                <div class="guide-cell">Simple, small-scale applications</div>
                <div class="guide-cell"><span style="color: #198754;">YES - Simple to start</span></div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="beginner-advice">
            <h4>Beginner's Recommendation</h4>
            <p><strong>Start with Microsoft SQL Server + C#!</strong> Here's why:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Excellent integration with C# and .NET</li>
                <li>Great for learning structured thinking</li>
                <li>Most jobs use relational databases</li>
                <li>You can use Entity Framework (makes it easy!)</li>
                <li>Free versions available for learning</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Don't worry - you'll use C# code, not complex SQL commands. The framework does the hard work for you!</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("WhyDatabase", "Database")" class="btn btn-outline-primary ajax-link">← Why Use a Database?</a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("HowDatabaseWorks", "Database")" class="btn btn-primary ajax-link">Next: How Databases Work →</a>
    </div>
</div>

